  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. This practice is considered illegal because it facilitates criminal activities and undermines the integrity of financial systems.\n\nIn China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law, enacted in 2007, explicitly prohibits money laundering activities and outlines stringent measures to combat them. The law mandates financial institutions and certain non-financial entities to establish internal control systems, report suspicious transactions, and collaborate with regulatory authorities to prevent and detect money laundering activities. Violations of these provisions can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nThe Chinese government remains committed to enforcing anti-money laundering regulations and collaborating with international entities to promote global financial security and stability.",
